evaluation.response:
It's clear that you've been through a tough time and are still dealing with some of those challenges. Here are some additional resources that might be really helpful:

*   **NEDA Helpline**: The National Eating Disorders Association has a very supportive hotline that's available to call or text at (800) 931-2237.&#x20;
*   **Therapy**: Talking to a therapist can be a really great way to work through some of these feelings and concerns. They can also help you develop some coping strategies and techniques to manage anxiety and other tough emotions. National Eating Disorders Association can help you find therapists or treatment centers local to you.

It sounds like you're feeling quite isolated. Here are a few things you could try that might help:

*   Recognize that you have anorexia and commit to recovery.
*   Eat high-calorie foods and follow a meal plan.
*   Practice yoga to help you cope with your emotions.
*   Look into therapy.&#x20;
*   Look into support groups.&#x20;

If you are not getting enough calories from your day-to-day activities in order to give your body the best chance of performing dance, there are some very logical physical symptoms that can occur. These can include quick physical fatigue, hair loss, brittle nails, poor wound healing, and also heart issues such as positional bradycardia.

Many professional dancers are at a weight much higher than you are right now. Other than a few select groups at anorexic BMI points - the very large majority of successful professional dancers run a normal BMI. Operation-level performing can also be achieved at high levels at an over weight BMI.&#x20;

If you are looking at ways you might be struggling so much with your anorexia it could be beneficial to further ask those around you or even yourself about yourself that you could possibly do to live your best life. Looking at the types of clothes you like to wear could be a good place to start. If you discover you like wearing size XXL and are at size XXS right now, know that it's ok to be at a weight that you're happy at if that makes you the best version of yourself during your day. Or if you look at the types of foods you like most which are career off-limit foods, then maybe there is another career that you're interested in that does limit you as much with only being able to consume certain foods.

These will just be good tools to further move you in a correct direction towards living your best self, but only you can truly know what is best for you by taking the proper time to educate yourself and use that education to make proper self-care choices.&#x20;
